\begin_layout Standard
At level 105 the Arena Manager mini-game unlocks.
 The goal is to gain runes, and once you collect 1000+, you can find items
 with rune bonuses.
 The more runes you have, the better those bonuses are.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the picture above you can see that the arena money and runes you have
 already gained are shown at the left side.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You start with one arena attraction (the seat).
 Attractions generate arena money (even when you are not online and playing).
 The more you improve the attractions, the more money they generate.
 You use the money to improve the attractions, so they generate more money.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the money you invested in your arena since the last sacrifice are automatica
lly converted to runes.
 That amount of runes is shown at the right side, as part of the [SACRIFICE]
 button.
 You can collect those runes by clicking the sacrifice button, resetting
 all your arena progress.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each rune gained increases with +5% the money profit from all attractions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
How to upgrade attractions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When you start, improve the attraction that has the lowest MIN price.
 It's a good rule to follow even later, but it also depends on how close
 the attraction is to the next milestone (25, 50, 100, 250, 500, 1000, 2500,
 5000, 10000).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each time an attraction reaches such a milestone, it doubles its profit,
 and reduces the time required to fill the attraction with 1/3.
 So, it makes sense to first upgrade attractions that are closer to the
 next milestone, even if they have a higher MIN price.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Likewise, when two attractions have a similar MIN price, it's more efficient
 to upgrade the one with less upgrades.
 For example, if you upgrade an attraction that reached 100+, it will boost
 the overall profit more than if you would upgrade a higher attraction that
 reached 500+.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another rule you can follow for efficient progress, is to keep difference
 between two consecutive attractions between 50 and 100 upgrades.
 This remains true until the very end of that game.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
How often to sacrifice
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When you start, if you have lots of time to rebuild the progress of the
 attractions, you can make first sacrifice when you have between 10 and
 20 runes waiting to be sacrificed.
 If you don't have too much time at that moment, wait for 20 runes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After that, until you collect about 1 million runes, sacrifice each time
 runes double their amount (the amount of runes waiting to be sacrificed
 at the button is the same as the amount of runes you have already gained).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's a good idea to sacrifice during the day, so you have enough time to
 rebuild attractions before the night.
 In this way they can accumulate more money while you sleep.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the toilet attraction reaches 1000 (or even if it reaches 500), you
 should start to sacrifice more often, not waiting for runes to double anymore
 (more than once per day).
 
\series bold
The ideal is to sacrifice every time the toilet attraction fills (1 cycle
 of toilet)
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reason for this is that last attractions generate the most arena cash,
 but they also have the largest amortization, so if you wait runes to double,
 amortization accumulates and last attractions are not that efficient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sacrificing each time the toilet attraction fills might be the fastest way,
 but since that takes way too much time, no one really does that.
 If you manage to sacrifice at least 5 times per day, you will still do
 better than most players.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
What boosts/offers to buy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What boosts to buy depends on your playstyle, so let's split that in 3 parts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Completely free to play
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Don't buy boosts on the first attractions at all and don't buy any skip
 offers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When you unlock last attraction, get both the speed and money boost for
 the toilet attraction (25+50 mushrooms).
 It takes time to collect those, but it's worth it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reason for buying boosts for last attraction only is that 
\series bold
each attraction generates almost as much as all other earlier attractions
 combined together
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Minimal usage of mushrooms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Don't buy boosts on the first attractions at all and don't buy any skip
 offers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When you unlock last two attractions (the toilet and straying monster),
 get both the speed and money boost for both of them (25+50+75+100 mushrooms).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Limited use of mushrooms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At first buy both the speed and money boosts for the first attraction only
 (the seat).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After that buy several 7-day skips in order to reach 1 million runes faster.
 At that amount you can find items with '+2% Hit point' runes.
 Equip 8 such items, and you will have a total of +15% extra hit points
 (the maximum you can get is +15%).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once you have those you can continue buying skip offers here and there,
 until you unlock the last 4 attractions.
 When that happens, buy both boosts for those last 4 attractions (toilet,
 straying monster, snacks and VIP seat).
 All those boosts (plus the first seat) cost 1300 mushrooms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Only continue buying 7-day skip offers until you reach 25% damage bonus.
 Following this start buying them only occasionally, for example if you
 feel it gets so slow that you just can't stand that (eg.
 between Tredecillion and Quattuordecillion).
 Check one of the next sections on tips how to force the merchant to offer
 you 7-day skips every day, even if you don't have all boosts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having 25% damage runes on the weapon will help you push early dungeons
 more easily.
 About the same time rune generation slows down to a crawl, so even if you
 had all boosts, you would still need to wait quite some time before you
 can equip any better weapon runes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And by the time you make progress to +30% damage runes, dungeons will be
 so difficult that those won't help you clear more than a few dungeon floors.
 In fact even the maximum of +60% damage bonus does not help too much.
 At best it will assist you to clear several floors and gain 1-2 levels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fastest way to max bonuses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you want to unlock the max rune bonuses in the fastest way possible,
 you need to buy absolutely all boosts, including the platinum ones (platinum
 boosts become available only after you have all speed and gold boosts),
 and to buy 7-day skips daily for about 100 days.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It costs 4300 mushrooms to buy all of them (including platinum boosts) and
 about 3000 mushrooms to buy enough 7-day skips.
 Of course that is expensive and not worth it.
 You can buy much less boosts and skips, and still reach the maximum bonuses
 in 6-12 months.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Getting 7-day skip offers daily
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a trick to force 7-day skips daily:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set an alarm about 1-2 hours before next arena offer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
When alarm rings, sacrifice arena progress, and only upgrade the seat, and
 the attractions that you already have both boosts for (eg.
 monster and toilet only).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set another alarm for 1 minute after next arena offer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
When alarm rings, open the offer (it is important to open the offer before
 improving other attractions, as offer is calculated the moment you open
 it, not when time expires).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Merchant can only offer you boosts for attractions that you are currently
 developing
\series default
, so he will be forced to offer you either a boost for the seat or offers
 for skips.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If there is a 7-day skip, don't rush to buy the offer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set another alarm for 15-30 minutes before the offer expires.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Immediately start increasing all attractions in order to develop them as
 much as possible before accepting the 7-day skip.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
When alarm fires buy the 7-day skip.
\end_layout

