\begin_layout Subsection*
Warnings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's first start with some warnings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reaching level 110-120 in first few days of a server is possible, but expensive.
 In the long run it makes no sense, and is a waste of mushrooms, unless
 you are aiming for a top rank on the server.
 Even if that is the case, you can only benefit from that, if you plan to
 keep pushing long-term.
 If you ever stop pushing at the same rate, other players who started slower
 (and cheaper) can catch up with you later, with overall less budget.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, pushing early, and then chilling in eco or free to play mode, is
 a complete waste, and only worth for the thrill.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Primary Goal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ambitious people aiming at top ranks sometimes do that in order to unlock
 Pets, Arena Manager and Underworld sooner.
 In this way they get an earlier advantage to most players in rune bonuses,
 pets, and the gladiator critical damage bonus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
The most important milestone is to reach level 50 at day #2, or at latest,
 in the morning of day #3
\series default
.
 Thus you can start buying epics from the shops before the initial multi-event
 is over.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It helps a lot, if you have a guild with the following requirements:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
4/6 (or 5/5) skills at the very start
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
everyone level 25+ at end of day #1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
everyone HoK 6 at end of day #1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Budget
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Expected cost is between 1K and 2K mushrooms per day
\series default
.
 The exact amount depends on the choice of class, previous experience and
 the guild.
 Given some luck, classes like berserker, scout and druid are more likely
 to defeat dungeon monsters that are of a much higher level than the player,
 so the cost for them is lower than for the rest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That's especially true for the berserker, as its rage attack ability sometimes
 allows it to kill an enemy without taking a single hit.
 This is also the only special class ability that also works against mages,
 which makes mage dungeons extremely easy for the berserker class.
 So, if you just want to try fast-leveling as an experiment, it would be
 
\series bold
most cost-efficient to do it with the berserker class
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pace of your progress is also influenced a lot by the guild bonuses
 and HoK.
 To make it cheaper, you need a guild where everyone plans to increase their
 guild skills to 4/6 (or 5/5) with the Starter Pack, at the very start of
 the server.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since in the beginning gem stats depend entirely on the guild HoK, it also
 helps a lot to be part of an ambitious guild.
 Better HoK means better gems and more stats, so you will find it easier
 to defeat dungeons earlier.
 This is only possible if everyone pushes to level 25+ at the end of day
 #1, in order to unlock the Fortress pack.
 The resources from that pack are necessary in order to skip to HoK 6 (costs
 only about ~130 mushrooms).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of the steps in this guide have been tested with a battle mage character,
 in an ambitious guild.
 It went a bit outside the budget, but if you use another class, it should
 work better.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Enough blabber, time for action.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
General tips
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When changing weapon 
\series bold
compare only maximum damage
\series default
 and stats, ignore minimum and average damage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If you can't find a good epic weapon, choose one with main stat only.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At lower levels you can use the following simple formula to calculate what
 
\series bold
maximum damage to look for in shops
\series default
: 
\shape italic
\bar under
MaxDamage = 3 x CharacterLevel + 15
\shape default
\bar default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
And the following formula for max item stats to look for: 
\shape italic
\bar under
MaxItemStats = 2 x CharacterLevel
\shape default
\bar default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Once you unlock Gem Mine, 
\series bold
only equip items with gem sockets
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
After you unlock Gem Mine, 
\series bold
keep base stats in 50/50 ratio
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Only increase luck while it's cheap.
 Having at least 15-20% chance for critical hits is good to have.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that finding items in shops with maximum possible damage or stats is
 expensive, so if you are given something relatively close to that, just
 take it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Farming gold
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When you are low on gold, and need that to raise stats, you can find players
 in the hall of fame that give the maximum gold possible (equal to their
 level), and attack them repeatedly until you steal all the gold.
 After the player drops too much in rank compared to you, you will stop
 earning any gold from him.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get around that, spend the gold, unequip as much of your equipment (especiall
y the weapon), and attack him a few times.
 Thus you raise him in rank, while lowering yourself.
 Equip your items again and continue attacking him until your are sure he
 has no more gold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you hear anyone talking about 'farming arena for gold', that is what
 he means.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to earn extra gold is to buy the 50% mount multiple times.
 Each time you buy it, you get an environmental gold reward.
 But be careful with that, as it is very expensive, especially before level
 35, and you can still progress enough without that.
 Yet, good to know.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you don't have enough gold to buy new equipment, or gems, or whatever,
 the above options can help you to proceed further without doing too much
 quests (saving the thirst for later).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Day 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Goals for end of day #1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Reach level 26+
\series default
 (34+ for berserkers/scouts/druids), although even a battle mage can reach
 level 31-32 on day #1, as long as you go outside of the budget enough;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Collect 45%-50% of album
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's start:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Join the guild.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Buy the Starter Pack.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Sell the hitpoints potion for 100 gold
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
